\begin_layout Standard
As control input, an onramp at junction 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{i}$
\end_inset

 and time 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 has a metering rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\ramp_{\link}^{\tind}\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 which limits the flux of vehicles leaving the onramp.
 The bounded domain of the metering control is to force the control to neither
 impose negative flows nor send more vehicles than present in a queue.
 Its mathematical model is expressed in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ramp-eqn"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The vehicle flow dynamics on all links 
\begin_inset Formula $\link$
\end_inset

 (mainlines, onramps, and offramps) are modeled using the LWR equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\density_{t}+f\left(\density\right)_{x}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\density$
\end_inset

 is the density state, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the derivative of the flux function (or fundamental diagram) 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\density\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We assume the fundamental diagram has a trapezoidal form as depicted in
 Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Fundamental-diagram-with"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For notational simplicity we define the set of densities of links adjacent
 to a junction 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{i}$
\end_inset

 at time-step 
\begin_inset Formula $\tind$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\juncstate{\link}{\tind}=\left\{ \densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind}{\text{Inc}},\densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind}{\text{Out}},\densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind}{\text{On}}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The offramp is considered to have infinite capacity, and thus has no bearing
 on the solution of junction problems.
 Taking a junction 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{i}$
\end_inset

 at time-step 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, we discretize the downstream mainline density 
\begin_inset Formula $\density_{i,k}^{\text{Out}}=\density_{i+1,k}^{\text{Inc}}$
\end_inset

 using the Godunov scheme from
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:main-ge"

\end_inset

 to obtain the discrete update equation on a mainline:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\syseq_{\link,\text{Out}}^{\tind}(\state,\control) & =\densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind}{\text{Out}}-\densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind-1}{\text{Out}} & +\dfrac{\Delta t}{\Delta x}\left(\god_{\jn_{\link+1}}\left(\juncstate{\jn_{\link+1}}{\tind-1},\ramp_{\link+1}^{\tind-1}\right)\right)_{\text{Inc}}\label{eq:rho-update}\\
 &  & -\dfrac{\Delta t}{\Delta x}\left(\god_{\jn_{\link}}\left(\juncstate{\jn_{\link}}{\tind-1},\ramp_{\link}^{\tind-1}\right)\right)_{\text{Out}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\length_{\link}$
\end_inset

 is the distance between junctions 
\begin_inset Formula $\jn_{\link}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\jn_{\link+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\god_{\jn_{\link}}\left(\juncstate{\jn_{\link}}{\tind},\ramp_{\link}^{\tind}\right)\right)_{\link}$
\end_inset

 is the flux from the boundary condition of density 
\begin_inset Formula $\juncstate{\link}{\tind}$
\end_inset

 at junction 
\begin_inset Formula $\jn_{\link}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\link\in\intrange 1{\nlinks}$
\end_inset

.
 We also make the assumption that onramps have infinite capacity and a length
 of one to prevent ramp congestion from block demand from ever entering
 the network.
 We can then simplify the onramp update equation to be:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\syseq_{\link,\text{On}}^{\tind}(\state,\control)=\densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind}{\text{On}}-\densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind-1}{\text{On}}+\frac{\triangle t}{1}\left(\left(\god_{\jn_{\link}}\left(\juncstate{\jn_{\link}}{\tind-1},\ramp_{\link}^{\tind-1}\right)\right)_{\text{On}}-\demand{\link}{\tind}\right)=0\label{eq:onramp-update}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\demand{\link}{\tind}$
\end_inset

 is the onramp 
\emph on
flux 
\emph default
demand, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\link\in\intrange 1{\nlinks}$
\end_inset

.
 This formulation results in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

strong
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 boundary conditions at the onramps which guarantees all demand enters the
 network.
 Details on weak versus strong boundary conditions can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ML,Walid,strub2006weak"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Riemann solver
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the ramp metering problem, there are many potential Riemann solvers
 that satisfy the properties required in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Network-of-PDE's"

\end_inset

.
 Following the model of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Walid,ML"

\end_inset

, for each junction 
\begin_inset Formula $\jn_{\link}$
\end_inset

, we add two modeling decisions: the flux solution maximizes the outgoing
 mainline flux 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\god_{\jn_{\link}}\left(\juncstate{\jn_{\link}}{\tind},\ramp_{\link}^{\tind}\right)\right)_{\text{Out}}$
\end_inset

, and any remaining non-uniqueness in the incoming flux is resolved using
 a merging parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This leads to the following system of equations that gives the flux solution
 of the Riemann solver at time-step 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\intrange 1{\ntime-1}$
\end_inset

 and junction 
\begin_inset Formula $\jn_{\link}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\link\in\intrange 1{\nlinks+1}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\delta & = & \min\left(v_{i}\densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind}{\text{Inc}},F_{\link,\text{Inc}}^{\max}\right)\label{eq:first-ramp}\\
\sigma & = & \min\left(w_{i}\left(\density_{i}^{\max}-\densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind}{\text{Out}}\right),F_{i,\text{Out}}^{\max}\right)\\
d & = & \ramp_{\link}^{\tind}\min\left((1)\densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind}{\text{On}},F_{i,\text{On}}^{\max}\right)\label{eq:ramp-eqn}\\
\left(\god_{\jn_{\link}}\left(\juncstate{\jn_{\link}}{\tind},\ramp_{\link}^{\tind}\right)\right)_{\text{Out}} & = & \min\left(\beta_{\link}^{\tind}\delta+d,\sigma\right)\\
\left(\god_{\jn_{\link}}\left(\juncstate{\jn_{\link}}{\tind},\ramp_{\link}^{\tind}\right)\right)_{\text{Inc}} & = & \begin{cases}
\delta & \frac{\sigma p_{i}}{1+p_{i}}\ge\frac{\delta}{\beta_{i,k}}\\
\frac{\left(\god_{\jn_{\link}}\left(\juncstate{\jn_{\link}}{\tind},\ramp_{\link}^{\tind}\right)\right)_{\text{Out}}-d}{\beta_{\link}^{\tind}} & \frac{\sigma}{1+p_{i}}\ge d\\
\frac{\sigma p_{i}}{\left(1+p_{i}\right)\beta_{\link}^{\tind}} & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}\\
\left(\god_{\jn_{\link}}\left(\juncstate{\jn_{\link}}{\tind},\ramp_{\link}^{\tind}\right)\right)_{\text{On}} & = & \left(\god_{\jn_{\link}}\left(\juncstate{\jn_{\link}}{\tind},\ramp_{\link}^{\tind}\right)\right)_{\text{Out}}-\beta_{i}^{\tind}\left(\god_{\jn_{\link}}\left(\juncstate{\jn_{\link}}{\tind},\ramp_{\link}^{\tind}\right)\right)_{\text{Inc}}\\
\left(\god_{\jn_{\link}}\left(\juncstate{\jn_{\link}}{\tind},\ramp_{\link}^{\tind}\right)\right)_{\text{Off}} & = & \left(1-\beta_{i}^{\tind}\right)\left(\god_{\jn_{\link}}\left(\juncstate{\jn_{\link}}{\tind},\ramp_{\link}^{\tind}\right)\right)_{\text{Inc}}\label{eq:last-ramp}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
, where, for simplicity of notation, any undefined state values (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\densitydiscrete 1{\tind}{\text{Inc}}$
\end_inset

 or
\begin_inset Formula $\densitydiscrete{\nlinks+1}{\tind}{\text{Out}}$
\end_inset

 ) are assumed to be zero.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\tind=0$
\end_inset

, the update equation is given by a pre-specified initial condition, as
 in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:init-ge"

\end_inset

.
 Note that the equations can be solved sequentially via forward substitution.
 Also, we only include the flux results for offramps explicitly here to
 demonstrate that indeed the flux solution satisfies the flux conservation
 property.
 We will ignore its explicit computation for the remainder of the article
 since its value has no bearing on further calculations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Optimal coordinated ramp-metering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Including the initial conditions as specified in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:init-ge"

\end_inset

 with
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:rho-update"

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:onramp-update"

\end_inset

 gives a complete description of the system 
\begin_inset Formula $\sys\left(\state,\control\right)=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\state\in\mathbb{R}^{2\nlinks}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\control\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\state_{2\nlinks\tind+2*\link-1}\defeq & \densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind}{\text{Out}}\defeq\densitydiscrete{\link+1}{\tind}{\text{Inc}} & 1\le i\le\nlinks,0\le k\le T-1\\
\state_{2\nlinks\tind+2*\link-1}\defeq & \densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind}{\text{On}} & 1\le i\le\nlinks,0\le k\le T-1\\
\control_{\nlinks\tind+\link}\defeq & \ramp_{\link}^{\tind} & 1\le i\le\nlinks,0\le k\le T-1
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The objective of the control is to minimize the 
\emph on
total travel time 
\emph default
on the network
\emph on
.
 
\emph default
This is expressed with the cost function 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J\left(\state,\control\right)=\triangle t\sum_{k=1}^{T}\sum_{i=1}^{\nlinks}L_{i}\densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind}{\text{Out}}+(1)\densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind}{\text{On}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the optimal coordinated ramp-metering problem can be formulated as
 a network PDE-constrained optimization problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\min_{\control} & \cost\left(\state,\control\right)\label{eq:full}\\
\text{subject to:} & \sys\left(\state,\control\right) & =0\nonumber \\
 & 0\le\convar\le1 & \forall\convar\in\control\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Since the adjoint method in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Adjoint-method"

\end_inset

 does not permit inequalities in the constraints, we add barrier penalties
 to the cost function
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Boyd2010,Bayen2006"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\cost}\left(\state,\control,R\right)=\cost\left(\state,\control\right)-R\sum_{\convar\in\control}\log\left(\left(1-\convar\right)\left(\convar-0\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\begin_inset Formula $R\in\mathbb{R}^{+}$
\end_inset

 tends to zero, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\cost}$
\end_inset

 tends towards 
\begin_inset Formula $\cost$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we can solve
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:full"

\end_inset

 by iteratively solving the augmented problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\min_{\control} & \tilde{\cost}\left(\state,\control,R\right)\label{eq:full-1}\\
\text{subject to:} & \sys\left(\state,\control\right) & =0\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with decreasing values of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 As a result, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\cost}$
\end_inset

 will approach 
\begin_inset Formula $\cost$
\end_inset

 as the number of iterations increases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Applying the adjoint method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To use the adjoint method as described in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Adjoint-method"

\end_inset

, we need to compute the partial matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hx$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{v}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{C}_{\state}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{C}_{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Computing the partial derivatives with respect to the cost function is
 straight forward:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\pfrac{\tilde{\cost}}{\densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind}{\text{Out}}}= & \triangle tL_{i} & 1\le i\le\nlinks,0\le k\le T-1\\
\pfrac{\tilde{\cost}}{\densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind}{\text{On}}}= & \triangle t & 1\le i\le\nlinks,0\le k\le T-1\\
\pfrac{\tilde{\cost}}{\ramp_{\link}^{\tind}}= & R\left(\frac{-1}{1-\ramp_{\link}^{\tind}}+\frac{1}{\ramp_{\link}^{\tind}}\right) & 1\le i\le\nlinks,0\le k\le T-1
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To compute the partials of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, we follow the procedure in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "par:Calculating-the-gradient"

\end_inset

.
 For a given junction 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{i}$
\end_inset

 and time-step 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, we only need to compute the partial derivatives of the flux solver 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}_{J_{i},k}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the adjacent state variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\vect{\density}_{J_{i},k}$
\end_inset

 and ramp metering control 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i,k}$
\end_inset

.
 We calculate the partials of the variables in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:first-ramp"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:last-ramp"

\end_inset

 for a junction 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{i},\link\in\intrange 1{\nlinks}$
\end_inset

 at time-step 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\intrange 1{\ntime-1}$
\end_inset

 with respect to either a state or control variable 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\pfrac{\delta}s & = & \begin{cases}
v_{i} & s=\densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind}{\text{Inc}},v_{i}\densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind}{\text{Inc}}\le F_{i,\text{Inc}}^{\max}\\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}\\
\pfrac{\sigma}s & = & \begin{cases}
-w_{i} & s=\densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind}{\text{Out}},w_{i}\left(\density_{i}^{\max}-\densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind}{\text{Out}}\right)\le F_{i,\text{Out}}^{\max}\\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}\\
\pfrac ds & = & \begin{cases}
\ramp_{\link}^{\tind} & s=\densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind}{\text{On}},\densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind}{\text{On}}\le F_{\link,\text{On}}^{\max}\\
\min\left(\densitydiscrete{\link}{\tind}{\text{On}},F_{i,\text{On}}^{\max}\right) & s=\ramp_{\link}^{\tind}\\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}\\
\pfrac{\left(\god_{\jn_{\link}}\left(\juncstate{\jn_{\link}}{\tind},\ramp_{\link}^{\tind}\right)\right)_{\text{Out}}}s & = & \begin{cases}
\beta_{\link}^{\tind}\pfrac{\delta}s+\pfrac ds & \beta_{i,k}\delta+d\le\sigma\\
\pfrac{\sigma}s & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}\\
\pfrac{\left\{ \hat{F}_{J_{i},k}\right\} _{\text{Inc}}}s & = & \begin{cases}
\pfrac{\delta}s & \frac{\sigma p_{i}}{1+p_{i}}\le\frac{\delta}{\beta_{i,k}}\\
\beta_{i,k}^{-1}\left(\pfrac{\left\{ \hat{F}_{J_{i},k}\right\} _{\text{Out}}}s-\pfrac ds\right) & \frac{\sigma}{1+p_{i}}\le d\\
\frac{p_{i}}{\beta_{i,k}\left(+p_{i}\right)}\pfrac{\sigma}s & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}\\
\pfrac{\left\{ \hat{F}_{J_{i},k}\right\} _{\text{On}}}s & = & \pfrac{\left\{ \hat{F}_{J_{i},k}\right\} _{\text{Out}}}s-\beta_{i,k}\pfrac{\left\{ \hat{F}_{J_{i},k}\right\} _{\text{Inc}}}s
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These expressions fully quantify the partial values needed in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:dhdugod"

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
